Electron: $e = -1.6 \times 10^{-19} \text{ C}$, $m_e = 9.1 \times 10^{-31} \text{ kg}$; 
Proton: $p = +1.6 \times 10^{-19} \text{ C}$, $m_p = 1.672 \times 10^{-27} \text{ kg}$; 
Neutron: charge = 0, $m_n = 1.674 \times 10^{-27} \text{ kg}$; 
Specific charge ($e/m$) = $1.75 \times 10^{11} \text{ C/kg}$

Dalton's Theory: Atom is the smallest indivisible unit; 
Isotopes: Same $Z$, Different $A$; 
Isobars: Same $A$, Different $Z$; 
Isotones: Same number of neutrons ($A-Z$); 
Isodiaphers: Same $(n-p)$ or $(A-2Z)$; 
Isosters: Same atoms and same electrons.

$c = \nu \lambda$; 
Wave number ($\bar{\nu}$) = $1/\lambda$; 
Energy ($E$) = $h\nu = \frac{hc}{\lambda}$; 
Planck's constant ($h$) = $6.626 \times 10^{-34} \text{ J} \cdot \text{s}$

$E = W_0 + K.E._{max}$; 
$h
u = h
u_0 +  rac{1}{2}mv^2$; 
Work function ($W_0$) = $h
u_0$ (threshold energy)

Angular Momentum: $mvr = \frac{nh}{2\pi}$; 
Radius: $r_n = 0.529 \times \frac{n^2}{Z} \text{ \AA}$; 
Energy: $E_n = -13.6 \times \frac{Z^2}{n^2} \text{ eV/atom}$; 
Velocity: $v_n = 2.18 \times 10^6 \times \frac{Z}{n} \text{ m/s}$

Rydberg Equation: $\bar{\nu} = R_H Z^2 \left[ \frac{1}{n_1^2} - \frac{1}{n_2^2} \right]$; 
$R_H = 109,677 \text{ cm}^{-1}$; 
Lyman ($n_1=1$, UV), Balmer ($n_1=2$, Visible), Paschen ($n_1=3$, IR)

Principal ($n$): Size, shell; 
Azimuthal ($l$): Shape, subshell ($0$ to $n-1$); 
Magnetic ($m_l$): Orientation ($-l$ to $+l$); 
Spin ($m_s$): Electron spin ($+1/2, -1/2$)

Radial Nodes = $n - l - 1$; 
Angular Nodes = $l$; 
Total Nodes = $n - 1$; 
Shapes: $s$ (spherical), $p$ (dumb-bell), $d$ (double dumb-bell)

Aufbau Principle: Fill lower $(n+l)$ first; 
Pauli Exclusion Principle: No two electrons have same 4 quantum numbers; 
Hund's Rule: Maximize spin multiplicity (singly occupy before pairing)
